    <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">Device Security</h1>
    <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
      Your phone and email are the keys to everything. These checklists focus on “high leverage” settings that prevent
      most real-world takeovers.
    </p>

    <section id="phone" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Phone checklist (iPhone & Android)</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
        <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          <li><strong>Update the OS</strong> and enable automatic updates.</li>
          <li><strong>Lock screen</strong>: strong passcode, disable lock-screen notifications for sensitive apps.</li>
          <li>
            <strong>App permissions</strong>: review Location, Microphone, Camera, Contacts; remove what isn’t needed.
          </li>
          <li><strong>Remove unknown profiles</strong> (especially on iOS) and unknown admin apps (Android).</li>
          <li><strong>Backups</strong>: ensure backups are on and you can restore them (Apple/Google).</li>
          <li><strong>SIM security</strong>: ask your carrier about a port-out/SIM-swap protection PIN.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="computer" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Computer checklist (Windows/macOS)</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
        <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          <li><strong>Updates</strong>: enable automatic OS + browser updates.</li>
          <li><strong>Disk encryption</strong>: FileVault (macOS) / BitLocker (Windows) if available.</li>
          <li><strong>Browser hygiene</strong>: remove suspicious extensions; keep only what you use.</li>
          <li><strong>Separate accounts</strong>: use a non-admin user for daily activity when possible.</li>
          <li><strong>Backups</strong>: Time Machine / Windows Backup; test a restore path.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="home-wifi" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Home Wi‑Fi & router basics</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          Your router is a “shared door” into every device on your home network. If you only do a few things, prioritize
          these.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          <li><strong>Change the router admin password</strong> (don’t leave the default).</li>
          <li><strong>Update router firmware</strong> (many routers have an “Update” section in settings).</li>
          <li><strong>Use strong Wi‑Fi encryption</strong> (prefer WPA3 if available; otherwise WPA2).</li>
          <li><strong>Turn off remote management</strong> unless you truly need it.</li>
          <li><strong>Create a guest network</strong> for visitors / smart devices when possible.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          Official guidance:
          <a
            class="font-semibold underline underline-offset-4"
            href="https://www.cisa.gov/news-events/news/home-network-security"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer"
            >CISA: Home Network Security</a
          >
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="safe-browsing" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Safe browsing & public Wi‑Fi</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
        <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          <li><strong>Keep browser extensions minimal</strong>; remove ones you don’t recognize.</li>
          <li><strong>Be careful on public Wi‑Fi</strong>: avoid sensitive logins when possible.</li>
          <li><strong>Prefer your phone hotspot</strong> for banking or account recovery flows.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          Official guidance:
          <a
            class="font-semibold underline underline-offset-4"
            href="https://www.cisa.gov/secure-our-world"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noreferrer"
            >CISA Secure Our World</a
          >
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="feel-monitored" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">If you feel monitored or harassed</h2>
      <div
        class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 p-6 text-amber-950 dark:border-amber-900/60 dark:bg-amber-950/40 dark:text-amber-100"
      >
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
          If you think you’re being stalked, digitally harassed, or threatened, your top priority is safety. Avoid “DIY
          forensics” that could destroy evidence or escalate conflict.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm">
          <li><strong>Preserve evidence</strong>: screenshots, URLs, dates/times, messages. Export where possible.</li>
          <li><strong>Secure your email</strong>: change password + enable MFA; review forwarding rules.</li>
          <li><strong>Change key passwords</strong> from a trusted device/network.</li>
          <li><strong>Tell a trusted person</strong> and create a check-in plan.</li>
          <li><strong>See Resources</strong> for reporting and support pathways.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>
